{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_carrie_ver01/data/sn85033078/00271768801/1921012001/0215.xml":{"full_text":"\u201cHE BEGAN BUSINESS ON HIS NERVE\nAND A SHOE-STRING.\u201d\nHow often we hear that remark. Investigation,\nhowever, frequently proves that\nThe \u201cshoe-string\u201d was a growing bank account;\nthe \u201cnerve\u201d confidence in himself which came as\nthe natural resula of a substantial reserve.\nThis institution cordially invites savings ac\ncounts no matter how small.\nWood County National Bank\nWISCONSIN RAPIDS, WIS.\n\u201cICI ET LA\u201d\nMrs. C. W. Bluett, Seventh street\nsouth entertained a company of\nfriends at her home Saturday eve\nning at \u201c500\u201d inhonor of her hus\nband's birthday. Mrs. G. Bean played\nladies high score, Mrs. A. J. Cowell\nheld lowest score for ladies, W. Fair\nbanks led with highest score for\ngentlemen and G Bean played low\nhand. At the conclusion of the games\nthe hostess served refreshments. An\nornamented birthday cake attracted\nmuch attention.\nIsaac Westplape, of Vesper, who\nwas badly burned about the limbs one\nday last week when he was lighting\na fire, is recovering slowly at River\nview hospital. Westplape was light\ning a fire in the forning and had\npoured in what he thought was kero\nsene on the wood. When he ignited\nit an explosion occured which burned\nhis left leg severely.\nThe adjourned term of the circuit\ncourt for Wood County will be called\nnext Monday morning when Judge\nByron B. Park will be here to hear\nany cases which may come up at that\ntime. While there are a number of\ncases scheduled the prediction made\nby attorneys are that the term will\nbe a short one, several of the lawyers\nbeing expected to ask for an adjoum\nment for their cases.\nA Medical Book Free\n\nBy Dr. N. A. Goddard\njytodern Methods of treating Chronic\nDiseases without Operation has\njust come from the Specialist and is\none of the most interesting as well as\ninstructive little books the doctor has\never written.\nIf You are a suf\ntdicitis, Rupture, Gall\nof a private nature,\u2019\nyourself of his offer\nto send you this val\nuable little book free\ning. A postal will Dr. Goddard\nbring it to you, in a plain wrapper.\nMany socalled surgical diseases have\nbeen proven to be cureable by medical\ntreatment more safely, more easily,\nand cheaply by modern medical meth\nods than was believed possible a few\nyears ago.\nAfter you have read this little book\nyou can consult Dr. Goddard on his\nmonthly visits to Grand Rapids, free\nof charge, and have the statifaction\nof knowing that you have secured the\nexpert opinion of a reputable special\nist in these matters. If you have been\nadvised to submit to an operation\nsurely do not fail to consult him be\nfore undergoing such an operation.\nHis advice may save you many weeks\nof suffering, loss of time, and expense,\npossibly your life.\nDr. Goddard will be at the Witter\nHotel, Grand Rapids, all day Thurs\nday, February 10th, and he makes no\ncharges for a friendly visit. Hours,\n9 a. m. to 6 n. m.\nAddress,\nDR. GODDARD,\n121 Wisconsin St.,\nMilwaukee, Wis.\nKellogg Bros. Lbr. Cos.\nBuilding\nHeadquarters\nYards at\nWisconsin Rapids, Nekoosa, Rudolph,\nVesper and Milladore\nMr. and Mrs. John Brundage who\nhave been visiting relatives in this\ncity for the past two weeks left Tues\nday morning for Minneapolis where\nthey will visit friends for a few days\nbefore returnh g to their home in\nAberdeen, South Dakota.\nA number of the friends and neigh\nbors of Mrs. Peter Love, surprised\nher at her home Saturday evening.\nThe occasion being the celebration of\nthe lady\u2019s birthday. The evening\nwas spent in a social way and at a\nlate hour fine refreshments were serv\ned. the guests not forgetting to bring\namong other good things to eat a\nbirthday cake prettily ornamented.\nMrs. Love was given many lovely\ngifts as a remembrance of the event.\nMi. Joseph Maher and son Law\nrence who have been guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Jacob Lutz, left Monday\nnoon for their home in Stanley, N.\nDakota.\nMiss Maine Conway left Monday\nmorning for Minneapolis to attend the\nwedding of her niece, Miss Marie\nBertram.\nH. F. Anderson of City Point, will\nmove his family back to this city to\nlive. He expects to buy an interest\nin the Sweet wagon works where he\nwas formerly owner. He sold out to\nMr. Sweet about three years ago and\nbought a farm at City Point. It did\ni not prove successful or satisfactory\nand he has come back again. We wel\ncome him back to our city.\nF. L. Felch, of Nekoosa, who has\nbeen held in the county jail here pend\ning the outcome of a charge of em\nbezzlement which was brought against\nhim by S. L. Stevens, was released\nThursday night on the condition that\nhe go to work. He has secured a\nposition in the woods near Park Falls\nand the case may be settled if he is\nable to pay up.\nWord has been received from Mr.\nand Mrs. Lafe Brooks who are spend\ning the winter at Los Angeles, Cal.,\nthat they are greatly enjoying the\ntrip. Mr. Brooks states that in the\nmiddle of the day when the sun shines\nit is like June and July weather in\nWisconsin. He has enjoyed several\nhunting trips and always succeeded\nin getting plenty of game, such as\nducks, rabbits and squirrels. Have\na fine market place where farmers\nbring their products three times a\nweek. Have been down to Tijuana!\nOld Mexico where they are having\n100 days horse races. Lots of people\ngo from here every day, you can get\nall kinds of drinks there, and men and\nwomen all gamble alike. It is neces\nsary to have a pass port both going\nand coming as no one is allowed to\ncarry anything either way. Besides\nthe races there is lots of all kinds of\nexcitement. They expect to return\nin their car over the southern trail\nthrough Texas and will follow the\nwarm climate all the way.\nMrs. Jennie G. Taylor, Witter St.,\nreturned Thursday from a three\nweek\u2019s visit at the home of her daugh\nter. Mrs. Daniel Arpin, Jr., and fam\nily in Bruce. Mrs. Taylor was ac\ncompanied by her grandson, Lawrence\nArpin, who will remain here for a\nweek or so.\nJudge W. H. Getts of this city has\nreceived word of the death of Mrs.\nElecta Getts, of Boise, Idaho, wife of\nhis brother, George M. Getts. Mrs.\nGetts-was buried by Rev. J. M. Baird\nand the Woman\u2019s Relief Corps took\ncharge of thg ttihefal at tht giAtfg.\nMrs Getts Was \"bom in Pennsylvania\nin 1884 and moved with her parents\nto Oregon, Wis., where she married\nGeorge M. Getts. Later they went\nwest and have lived in Boise for the\npast twenty years. She was quite\nw r ell known here, having visited with\nMr. and Mrs. W. H. Getts here several\ntimes.\nWarren Wright, a lifelong resident\nof Hancock, died at his home at that\nplace on Monday noon, following an\nillness of several years Mr. W T right\nwas more than 80 years of age and\nleaves six children. Funeral services\nwere conducted at Hancock Friday,\nburial followed in a cemetery there.\nWm, Berg finished up his fourteen\nth year on the police force of this\ncity on Thursday, having in more ser\nvice than any man on the force. Mr.\nBerg started out under the reign of\nChief Gibson and has had many ex\nperiences in his long service.\nMr. and Mrs. Chas. Fox of Rudolph\nare visiting at the home of their son,\nEd. Fox and family. They were spon\nsors at the baptismal services of their\nfirst grandson, Earl Charles Fox,\nwhich was held at SS Peter Paul\u2019s\nCatholic church.\nMAKING SHOP IMPROVEMENTS\nFerd. Link is making several im\nprovements in his meat market so\nthat he can carry a larger stock of\ncanned goods. He has reduced his\nshelving to a lower level and intends\nto move his counter out farther into\nthe sales room. He may decide to\ngo into the delicatessen branch of his\nline of business. He expects to take\ngood care of his trade.\nWAUSAU OPENS WAR\nON GAMBLING DEVICES\nWAUSAU\u2014A campaign against\nslot machines and punch boards is in\nprogress here. A raid resulted in\nconfiscation of six slot machines and\none punch board.\nFour offenders pleaded guilty and\nwere fined SSO and costs each. The\niounch board operator is to be tried\nFriday.\nIt is expected the law enforcement\ncrusade will be carried into the coun\ntry districts, where there are many\ngambling devices in operation.\nON EXTENDED TRIP\nS. N. Whittlesey left Wednesdav\nnoon, for Milwaukee, Wis., Chicago,\n111., San Antonia, Texas and Salt Lake\nCity. LTtah, and will continue his\njourney from the latter place to Long\nBeach, Cal., where he will meet his\nbrother, Henry H. Whittlesey and\nfrom where they will journey togeth\ner by motor thru all the principal\ncities of interest in California, and\nexpects to be gone until the first of\nApril.\nURGES $1,500 SALARY\nFOR BADGER SOLONS\nMADISON\u2014A resolution to raise\nthe salary of legislators to $1,500 was\nintroduced by Senator G. F. Czerwin\nski, Milwaukee. A constitutional\namendment is necessary to bring\nabout the proposed increase.\nThe present salary of SSOO a term is\nbranded by legislators as \u201cridiculous\nly low'\u2019 and there is a determined\nmovement on foot to raise the salary\nand cut down the length of the term\nto a point where service will be made\nattractive and will draw the best men.\nThe attempt to increase legislators\u2019\nsalaries, which failed at a vote in 1919\nwas defeated, it said, because\nits adoption would have given the leg\nislature blanket authority to grant\nitself, without limit, any salary. The\nbill of Senator Czerwinski definitely\nsets the salary at $1,500 a term, with\nno additional compensation for special\nsession other than railroad fare.\nWEST SIDE LUTHERAN CHURCH\nAt the annual meeting of the West\nSide Lutheran Church the financial\nsecretary reported that in spite of\nthe fact that the remaining debt had\nbeen paid, and substantial raises in\nsalary had been given the pastor,\nteachers and organist, his accounts\nstill showed a surplus. Many mem\nbers have been added to the congre\ngation the past year which now num\nbers about two hundred families.\nTo become better acquainted with\nits new\u2019 members the congregation\nheld a reception for them Tuesday\nevening at eight o\u2019clock in the school\nhouse. The pastor extended the wel\ncome to all, basing his remarks on\nRomans 12, 10. Miss Helen Zeister\nrendered a piano selection, \u201cSextette\nfrom Lucia de Lammermoor.\u201d Ferdi\nnand Frank gave the sacred poem\nentitled \u201cReformation,\u201d and the choir\nsang the song \u201cPraise Waitheth for\nThee,\u2019 as well as many other songs.\nThe rest of the evening w r as spent in\ncommunity singing and in amuse\nments. Refreshments were served by\nthe Mesdames Marry Oberbeck, Clara\nBethke, Fred Behrend, Emil Billare\nand G. M. Thurow.\nFISH\nFrozen direct from fishery to you.\nHerring rnd. per lb. 4 \\'i la r ge dress\ned sc, sknd. ready fry 7c; Bay fish\n(Suckers) dressed 4'/2c; Perch round\n4c, snd. dressed ready to fry 9c. Remit\nwith order or send for complete price\nlist.\nCONSUMERS FISH COMPANY,\nBay. Wisconsin\nMISS JANE\nGOUDE FINE\nELOCUTIONIST\nThe second number on the Com\nmunity Entertainment course took\nplace at Daly\u2019s theatre Wednesday,\nevening. The second number should\nhave been filled by Miss Bernice Ladd,\nwho was advertised on the course,\nbut it was filled by Miss Jane Goude\nof California, who proved to be an\nexcellent substitute. In spite of the\ninclement weather the opera house\nwas well filled. Her audience was\nlarge and fully appreciative of her ex\ncellent readings. Miss Gaude has a\npleasant way with her and her ap\npearance wins her audience immedi\nately. Every number rendered was\nfirst class and heartily encored. The\nsubstitute of person was highly sat\nisfactory.\nPRODUCERS AND CONSUMERS\nWILL GET NEARER TOGETHER\nAT BIG MARKET CONFERENCE.\n\u201cWhat are we going to do about it?\u201d\nWisconsin\u2019s agricultural forces have\nheai-d this query and accepted this\nchallenge until they propose to find\nout if anything can be done 1 to\n\u201cstraighten the road\u201d between the\nfarm field and the family table.\nThey appreciate that true to predic\ntions prices\u2014at least some prices\u2014\nhave fallen but they also realize that\nfarm prices have fallen first and far\nthest. Thus the constantly widening\ngap between producer and consumer\nis still further widened.\n\u201cAre there unnecessary dams in\nthe channels of trade\u2014unnecessary\ntransfers of cargo\u2014unnecessary dis\ntances covered?\u201d If so can not these\nobstructions be removed, this rehand\nling prevented, and these hauls\nshortened without disturbance to the\norderly procedure of legitimate pro\nduction and transfer?\nTo work out plans for \u201cdoing some\nthing\u201d about it all of the state\u2019s agri\ncultural forces will meet in one of the\nbiggest and most comprehensive \u201cGet-\nTogether Market Conferences\u201d yet\nplanned in America at the Agricultur\nal College, Madison, February 1-10.\nThe Agricultural College, the De\npartment of Agriculture, the Division\nof Markets, the Wisconsin live stock\nbreeders\u2019 association, the Wisconsin\nDairymans\u2019 Association, the Wiscon\nsin Farm Bureau Federation, the Wis\nconsin Potato Growers\u2019 Association,\nand all other organizations of farmers\nwill meet with the manufacturers, dis\ntributors, and consumers of farm pro\nducts for an earnest consideration of\nthe defiant question, \u201cWhat are we\ngoing to do about it?\u201d\nNever before, in a time of abundant\ncrops was the prosperity of the coun\ntry more seriously threatened. Many\nare unable to pay their debts \u2014labor-\ners are being thrown out of work\u2014\nthe buying power of the country is\nbeing continually lessened. Can any\nthings be done ab<^u f it It is certain\nthat nothing will be done until all in\nterested parties \u201cget together\u201d in an\neffort to do something. Nothing of\nvalue to the public at large will be\ngained by \u201cstrikes\u201d and \u201clook outs\u2019\nand \u201claying off\u201d men, and \u201ccancell\ning orders and all the other purely\ntemporary and artificial props to in\ndividual business. What we all need\nis accurate knowledge of world facts\nand an honest effort to meet world\nconditions as they exist rather than\nplaying for class or individual ad\nvantage.\nThe farmers\u2019 prices, to day, are de\ntermined largely by world conditions\n\u2014the prices paid by the consumer of\nhis products are too often artificially\nand locally controlled. The \u201cGet To\ngether Market Conference\u201d proposes\nto get at facts, remove unnecessary\nobstructions, smooth and straighten\nthe road.\nIt is to the interest of both farmer\nand packer that they consider together\nthe question of cooperative marketing\nof live stock and its products, to un\nderstand each other\u2019s point of view\nand to work out a practical method\nof doing business acceptable to both\nparties. It is likewise to the interest\nof the pea grower and the pea packer,\nthe sugar beet grower and the sugar\nfactory operator, the sheepman and\nthe woolen manufacturers, the dairy\nman and the consumer of his products\nto \u201cget together\u2019\u2019 for a consideration\nof mutual problems. It is of no less\ninterest to the consumer that waste\nand inefficiency in the distribution be\neliminated since in a very large degree\nhe will be the chief beneficiary. If\nprices are thus lessened to him his\ndollar will buy more. This will add\nto his consuming ability, which in\nturn will reflect itself in a better mar\nket for raw materials and resultant\nmanufactured products.\nTo \u2018\u2018get together\u201d on these problems\nwill injure no one and will ultimately\nwork to the benefit of all.\nThe one man in America who knows\nabout world food conditions and world\nmarkets for raw products\u2014outside of\nHerbert Hoover\u2014is Alonzo Taylor of\nPennsylvania, who, thruout the war\nand since has divided his time between\nthis country and Europe in a study of\nthese questions. His information is\nfirst hand. He has collected his own\nstatistics and observed conditions him\nself.\nMr. Tayior will open the \u201cGet To\ngether Conference\u201d with a discussion\nof the two topics upon which any con\nstructure marketing program must ul\ntimately rest\u2014\u201c The World\u2019s Tood\nSupply\u201d and *'fhi Weld's Shifts\nFrom the \u201cGet Together*' Confer 7\nence he will leave immediately for\nNew York to embark for Europe\nwhere he will continue his study and\nobservation oi European economic\nconditions.\nNORTHWESTERN TRAIN\nHITS TRUCK; 1 KILLED\nREEDSBURG\u2014One man was killed\nand another seriously injured when a\n\u2018southbound Northwestern passenger\ntrain struck a coal truck here. Jos\neph Sieks, 45, an inmate of the Sauk\ncounty hospital, was instantly killed.\nFrank Fulton, 20, the driver of the\ncar, suffred a broken collar bone and\ninternal injuries. The truck was de\nmolished and the engine of the train\nwas so badly damaged that it had to\nbe abandoned at Baraboo. Fulton\nclaims he was watching a switch en\ngine and did not see the approaching\npassenger train.\nMiss Irmia Johnson, daughter of\nMrs. Nels Johnson, slipped and fell\non the slippery sidewalk Wednesday\nand fractured her wrist.\nHOSPITAL NOTES\nDorothy Lane of Nekoosa, under\nwent an operation for the removal of\ntonsils at the Riverview Hospital\nTuesday.\nNorma Eberius, age eleven, and\nLeonard Eberius age nine, of Route\n8 were both operated on Tuesday for\nappendicitis at the Riverview Hos\npital.\nJulia Klepin, 1237 West Cleveland\nStreet, underwent an operation at\nthe hospital Wednesday morning,\nMrs. Stoltz of Nekoosa left Wed\nnesday for her home, after having\nbeen a patient at the hospital for\nsome time.\nCAUSEOFPRES\nENT DEPRESSION\nMADISON\u2014That the present state\nof business depression rests upon the\nfundamental unsoundness of our eco\nnomic system, is the view of Director\nNordman of the Market Division ex\npressed in a statement issued today.\n\u201cThe remedy does not lie in a change\nfeeling,\u201d says Mr. Nordman, \u201cor in\nthe assumption of an air of optimism\nas is advocated by some. The diffi\nculties which the country is going\nthrough are not products of imagina\ntion nor are they the result of the\nwar alone. The economic defects\nwhich produced them existed long ago.\nThe war has only intensified these dif\nficulties and no amount of optimistic\nnewspaper publicity, of soothing pro\nphecies as to the future or of the pat\nching up and restoring confidence pro\ncesses will ever eliminate them.\u201d\n\u201cConditions are not economically\nsound when the farmer cannot sell at\na fair and just price all he produces,\nand the consumer is not in a position\nto buy all he reasonably needs; they\nare not sound while many legalized\nprivileges exist in the country, as are\nshown to exist by the vast fortunes\nand stupendous incomes acquired. I\nam not speaking of fortunes earned;\nthe owners of these have conferred\nbenefits upon society greater than\nthat which they acquired.\u201d\n\u201cThe farmer\u2019s full share of the price\nof his products is considerably reduced\nbecause of inflated land values, a mo\nnopolistic control of the market in\ncertain lines of trade, and the waste\nand unnecessary expenses inherent in\nour system of distribution. On the\nother hand, the consumer\u2019s share of\nhis earnings is reduced by the legal\nized privileges which result in enor\nmous incomes acquired by a privileg\ned few. If a considerable minority\nhas the power to acquire more than\nit is rightfully entitled to, it logical\nly follows that the majority gets less\nthan that to which it has a just claim.\nThis majority will have to deprive it\nself of much that it needs, thus mak\ning less demands on the commodities\nwhich are produced. And here is\nthe fundamental cause of poor mar\nkets, of more commodities being pro\nduced than are sold, of bad times, un\nemployment, and all the other condi\ntions that everyone is complaining\nof.\u201d\nMr. Nordman believes it to be one\nof the duties imposed on his office to\ncall attention to what is deemed to\nbe the causes of the present business\ndepression. The remedies for these\ntroubles are discussed in the press\nletters which the Division of Mar\nkets is periodically issuing.\nPROSECUTIONS FOR\nVIOLATION OF LAW\nMADlSON\u2014Seventeen cases for\nprosecution were filed with district at\ntorneys Thursday by the Division of\nMarkets for violation of the state\nstandards relating to grades for po\ntatoes and honey.\nThe offences alleged are in Dane,\nEau Claire, Chippewa, Waupaca,\nSauk. Brown, Waushara, Ashland,\nMarinette, and Portage counties.\nConvictions have recently been ob\ntained in Fond du Lac, Langlade, Jun\neau, and Ashland counties.\nThe Division of Markets suggests,\nin recommendations for changes in its\nlaw, the method of enforcing the\nstate standards be changed from crim\niiiit F-fSrtfcUtieh ta liciftiitig\niiiid somptiUory lice need inspection tt\nis pointed out that the pfesent method\nof inspection reaches only the occa\nsional case while the plan of licens\ning dealers generally and requiring\nlicensed inspection on all shipments\nwould cover practically the entire\ncommercial crop. Moreover, it is em\nphasized that revocation of a ware\nhouseman\u2019s license to inspect means\nthat he cannot avail himself of the\nstate grades, which fact is calculated\nto act as a deterrent against mis\ngrading. This is the system employed\nin federal inspection under the grain\nstandards act.\nThe Division of Markets further re\nquests the power to issue an operating\nlicense to buyers of potatoes and\nother farm products, which may be\nwithdrawn and thus suspend the\nparty\u2019s right to do business for any\nviolation of standards or other lawful\nregulations issued by the Division of\nMarkets.\nThe suggestion has been made that\nthe grading of products should be\nmade mandatory, as in Nebraska, and\nthat the selling of \u201cungraded\u201d stock\nshould be flatly prohibited. The pre\nsent Wisconsin law reserves the right\nto any shipper to mark his product\n\u201cungraded,\u201d if it does not conform to\nthe requirements of the grade. The\ncontemplated proposal is to keep such\ninferior quality off of the market al\ntogether.\nThe Division of Markets, however,\nhas not yet advanced such a provision\ninasmuch as there seems some doubt\nas to the constitutionality of a law\nwhich would bar absolutely the mar\nketing of goods merely because they\nwere below the state standard in qual\nity.\nGRAND RAPIDS MARKETS\nSelling Prices\nFlour\u2014\nVictoria, per bbl. $12.00\nPillsbury, per bbl. $12,80\nRye, per bbl. 9.50\nBeans, per cwt. 8.5 C\nBarley, per bbl 9.00\nShelled corn, per cwt. 1.70\nMiddlings, per cwt. 1.80\nDry Onions, per bu. 1.75\nPeas, per cwt 4.50\nBran, per cwt. 1.80\nCornmeal, per cwt. 1.80\nFeed, 80 lb. sack 1.65\nBuckwheat flour, per bbl $13.00\nBuying Prices\nWheat No. 1 1.60\nOats, per bu. .48\nRye grain, per bu. 1 1.30\nPotatoes, per cwt 1.25\nLive hogs, per cwt. 8.00\nDressed hogs, per cwt. 12.50\nLive Beef, per cwt $2.50 to $7.00\nDressed Beef, per vwt._s7.oo to $13.00\nEggs, per dozen .65\nButter, per lb. .45\nLive hens, ped lb. 18c to 22c\nSpring chickens, per lb 18c to 22c\nHay per ton $15.00 to $22.00\nBEHERMMEIS\nEvery group, concerned with the\nreadjustment of Wisconsin\u2019s agricul\nture and allied industries to present\nlay conditions, will be represented in\nthe \u201cGet Together Market Confer\nence\u201d to be held in Madison, February\n1 to 10.\nEvery organization of state-wide\nscope is being invited to participate in\nthe convention. And the representa\ntives of these groups are inviting to\nmeet with them to consider these de\nfinant questions, manufacturers, dis\ntributors and consumers of farm pro\nducts.\nPlans for the convention are being\nlaid by officials of the various bodies\nrepresented. The subjects to be con\nsidered in the course of the conference\ninclude possible legislation to make\ncredit readily available to the farm\ners, means of improving the trans\nportation facilities of the state, and\nother problems of interest to the con\nsumer and producer. Out of this pro\ngram it is planned to develop a state\nagricultural policy.\nThe one man in America who knows\nmost about world food conditions and\nworld markets for raw products, out\nside of Herbert Hoover, is Dr. Alonzo\nE. Taylor. He will be at the confer\nence to give the information he has\ncolected. Thruout the war and since\nhe has divided his time between this\ncountry and Europe in a study of the\nvery questions which every farmer is\nasking. He leaves the conference to\nsail to the continent to continue his\nobservations of economic conditions.\nHe will discuss: \u201cThe World\u2019s Food\nSupply\u201d and \u201cThe World\u2019s Buying\nPower.\u201d\n\u201cWe propose to find out if anything\ncan be done to straighten the road be\ntween the farm field and the family\ndinner table,\u201d say the officials of the\nprospective conference. \u201cTrue to ex\npectation, farm prices have fallen first\nand farthest and the constantly wid\nening gap between producer and con\nsumer is still further spread apart.\n\u201cThe farmer\u2019s prices today, are de\ntermined largely by world conditions.\nThe prices paid by the consumer of his\nproducts are too often artificially and\nlocally controlled. Wisconsin\u2019s agri\ncultural forces propose to get at the\nfacts, remove unnecessary obstruc\ntions, smooth and straighten the\nr^ad.\u201d\nKEEPING\nRECORDS ON\nTHE FARM\nW ith the ever increasing complex\nity in the farm business, the neces\nsity of keeping an account of what\nhas taken place on the farm from year\no year asserts itself more and more.\nIt is a poor business, indeed, that does\nnot warrant some system of account\ning, some means by which the busi\nness man can work out an annual\nstatement of his affairs and learn\nthereby whether he is coming or go\ning. The accounting side of the farm\ning industry has been too much ne\nglected, and w'hen the immensity of\nthe totals concerned with the industry\nire considered the necessity of this an\nnual checking up stands out all the\nmore.\nOur leaders in agricultural affairs\noften find difficulty in progressing wirh\ncertain measures because of the lack\nof the information that farm account\nsystems would yield them. In manip\nulating for better prices, more stable\nmarkets, enacting more favorable\nlaws, the information that cost ac\ncounts acord is of great value. The\nkeeping of accounts also saves more\nor less of annoyance at income tax\ntime.\nThe farmer cannot be blamed great\nly, however, for not having taken to\nthe accounting work, since with his\nlimited time, he has been loath to\ntackle the complicated systems that\nhave been offered.\nThe College of Agriculture at Madi\nson has taken the lesson that these\nearlier attempts have offered, and\nhave produced a Farm Account Book\nthat is simple in its working, yet\nthorough in the results that it yields.\nI have a supply of these books on hand\nat the present time and will be glad\no co-operate with any one that wishes\nto start in with a good system of\n\u201d3\u2122 accounts. The book is simple\nind has been stripped of all technical\nterms that are not of general use and\n3ssential to the system. Only one\nwriting is necessary\u2014thereby elimi\nnating the bug-a-boo \u201cposting.\u201d A\ncharge of fifty cents is made for each\nbook.\nSpecialists are sent out from the\nCollege to cooperate with the County\nAgents in this work. If a few farmers\n\u2022are to get together to have the work\ndiscussed I shall be glad to meet with\nyou, or if you care to hold a Farm\nAccount school in your district, we\n\u2019an arrange to get the specialist here\nfrom Madison.\nR. A. Peterson, Cos. Agent.\nNOTICE FOR ADMINISTRATION\nAND NOTICE TO CREDITORS.\nState of Wisconsin, County Court,\nWood County\u2014ln Probate.\nIn Re Estate of Lucy E. Wood\nworth, deceased.\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN, That\nat the general term of said Court to\nbe held on the Ist Tuesday (being the\nIst day) of March, A. D. 1921, at the\nCourt House in the City of Wisconsin\nRapids, County of Wood and State of\nWisconsin, there' will be heard and\nconsidered the application of F. S.\nWoodworth for the appointment of an\nadministrator of the estate of Lucy\nE. Woodworth late of the City of Pit\ntsville, Wis., in said County, deceased.\nNOTICE IS HEREBY FURTHER\nGIVEN, That at the term of said\nCourt to be held at said Court House,\non the 4th Tuesday, (being the 24th\nday) of May A. D. 1921, there will\nbe heard, considered and adjusted, all\nclaims against said Lucy E. Wood\nworth, deceased;\nAND NOTICE IS HEREBY FUR\nTHER GIVEN, That all such claims\np or examination and allowance must\nbe presented to said County Court at\nthe Court House, in the City of Wis\nconsin Rapids, in said County and\nState, on or before four months from\nthe date hereof, or be barred.\nDated January 18th, 1921.\nBy the Court,\nW. J. Conway, County Judge.\nFIND FARMER DEAD\nIN POWER HOUSE\nPLAINFIELD\u2014Henry Timm, a\nfarmer, was found dead in his gasoline\npower house. It is believed death re\nsulted either from heart failure or\nfrom fumes of gasoline.\nHis wife and children had been gone\nall week, as his children attended high\nschool in Almond and his wife re\nmained with them to keep house. Mr.\nTimm always went after them each\nweek, but this time he did not come.\nHis wife telephoned to neighbors,\nwho went to his farm and found him\ndead. From appearances he had been\ndead several days.\nDEATH OF\nMRSi, IKING\nA telegram was received by Mr. C.\nO. Baker Wednesday from Mr. E. T.\nKing, St. Peterberg, Florida, announc\ning the death of his wife on Tuesday\nthe 18th of January, 1921, of Paral\nysis. He received no particulars as\nto the funeral, but that will probably\noccur in this city. Her obituary will\nappear in this paper next week.","height":"29631","width":"22635"}}
